# Server-Side Performance

## React.cache() for Per-Request Deduplication

Wrap expensive server-side functions with `React.cache()` so multiple components calling the same function in one request only execute it once:

```ts
import { cache } from 'react';

export const getCurrentUser = cache(async () => {
  const session = await auth();
  if (!session?.user?.id) {
    return null;
  }
  return await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: session.user.id } });
});
```

Use primitive arguments (not inline objects) — `cache()` uses `Object.is` for equality:

```ts
// Bad: inline object = cache miss every time
const getUser = cache(async (params: { uid: number }) => { ... });

// Good: primitive arg = proper cache hits
const getUser = cache(async (uid: number) => { ... });
```

Use `React.cache()` for: DB queries, auth checks, heavy computations, file system operations. Next.js already deduplicates `fetch()` calls automatically.

## Minimize Serialization at RSC Boundaries

Only pass the fields a Client Component actually uses. RSC→client serialization embeds all props in the HTML:

```tsx
// Bad: serializes all 50 user fields
const user = await fetchUser();
return <Profile user={user} />;

// Good: serializes only what's needed
const user = await fetchUser();
return <Profile name={user.name} avatarUrl={user.avatarUrl} />;
```

Avoid transforming arrays server-side when the client needs the original too (`.toSorted()`, `.filter()`, `.map()` create new references that get serialized separately):

```tsx
// Bad: sends both arrays
<ClientList users={users} activeUsers={users.filter((u) => u.active)} />

// Good: filter in client
<ClientList users={users} />
```

## Parallel Data Fetching via Component Composition

Sibling async Server Components fetch in parallel. Restructure sequential fetches into independent components:

```tsx
// Bad: sidebar waits for header fetch to finish
async function Page() {
  const header = await fetchHeader();
  return (
    <div>
      <div>{header}</div>
      <Sidebar />
    </div>
  );
}

// Good: both fetch simultaneously
async function Header() {
  const data = await fetchHeader();
  return <div>{data}</div>;
}

async function Sidebar() {
  const items = await fetchSidebarItems();
  return <nav>{items.map(renderItem)}</nav>;
}

function Page() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <Sidebar />
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Avoid Shared Module State for Request Data

Module-level mutable variables leak data between concurrent requests in RSC/SSR. Keep request data local to the render tree:

```ts
// Bad: race condition between concurrent requests
let currentUser: User | null = null;

export default async function Page() {
  currentUser = await auth();
  return <Dashboard />;
}

// Good: pass as props
export default async function Page() {
  const user = await auth();
  return <Dashboard user={user} />;
}
```

Safe exceptions: immutable config/constants, intentional shared caches with proper keys.

## Use after() for Non-Blocking Side Effects

Use Next.js `after()` to schedule work after the response is sent (logging, analytics, cache invalidation):

```ts
import { after } from 'next/server';

export async function POST(request: Request) {
  await updateDatabase(request);

  after(async () => {
    await logUserAction({ userAgent: request.headers.get('user-agent') });
  });

  return Response.json({ status: 'success' });
}
```

## Hoist Static I/O to Module Level

Static assets (fonts, logos, config) that don't change per-request should be fetched once at module level, not inside every request handler:

```ts
// Bad: reads file on every request
export async function GET() {
  const template = await fs.readFile('./template.html', 'utf-8');
  return new Response(template);
}

// Good: reads once when module loads
const template = fs.readFileSync('./template.html', 'utf-8');

export async function GET() {
  return new Response(template);
}
```

Source: Vercel React Best Practices
